[{"sha":"cc46e4c8f065cd90077fcb579a3a60927f27907b","author":{"email":"adb666e4c99945ba3cee762e30201b8c3c9c71fc@google.com","name":"Terry Heo"},"message":"PR #50615: [TFLite] Avoid passing negative quantized multipliers to MultiplyByQuantizedMultiplier

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/50615

Hello,

This PR updates the SUB and DIV kernels to avoid passing negative quantized multipliers to the `MultiplyByQuantizedMultiplier` method.

It allows us to later on add a restriction on the quantized multiplier of the int32 `MultiplyByQuantizedMultiplier` similar to the one already present in the int64 version.

Thibaut
Copybara import of the project:

bb1cb842e5a373be2862690010160b793dd35b3e by Thibaut Goetghebuer-Planchon <thibaut.goetghebuer-planchon@arm.com>:

Fix int16 SUB kernel to take into account the quantization scaling/zero-point

--
b65f25db31e47adb02da0375ed2c75ac01ca7686 by Thibaut Goetghebuer-Planchon <thibaut.goetghebuer-planchon@arm.com>:

Update SUB operator tests to have different scaling in the inputs and outputs

The change provides a more in-depth testing of the SUB operator. Previously the same scaling was used for both inputs and for the output, a simple subtraction in the kernel without any rescaling would have made the tests pass.

Implement class `OneHotMeanIoU` that inherits class `MeanIoU`.

This class can be used to compute the mean IoU metric for a multi-class classification task where both the labels are one-hot encoded.

[{"sha":"bb42c1c121cca7259c6801afd047b94e09a7a603","author":{"email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org","name":"A. Unique TensorFlower"},"message":"Fix a bug in the Estimator warm start framework which prevents two variables from being warm-started from the same tensor.

The [documentation](https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/estimator/WarmStartSettings) for the `var_name_to_prev_var_name` argument to `tf.estimator.WarmStartSettings` does not mention that two variables cannot be warm-started from the same previous variable.  But the current implementation does not support it, because it uses [`init_from_checkpoint`](https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/compat/v1/train/init_from_checkpoint), which accepts a reversed dict from previous variable name to current variable name.

This CL extends the implementation to make repeated calls to `init_from_checkpoint` whenever a previous tensor is found to initialize a second/third/... variable.

[{"sha":"f97b1ec19087fe0cf49fc67446bc78b059aef613","author":{"email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com","name":"Katherine Wu"},"message":"Make functions subclass Trackable.

This paves the way to removing the special-casing for functions when saving and loading. In this CL, `list_functions` has been removed from the _AugmentedGraphView and combined with `list_children`, because with this change, functions are just another Trackable child.

Some unpleasantness when gathering the children: because functions were not previously trackable, classes that override `_list_functions_for_serialization` may be excluding tracked Functions. One example is Keras (the `train_function` is purposely excluded from `_list_functions_for_serialization`). These cases will need to be dealt with individually during the migrations.

Rollforward notes: Special case the "signatures" tf.function dependency. This follows the previous signatures validation behavior where `list_children` did not return tf.functions at all, so it did not error out if the root object had a function in the `signatures` attribute.
